Q1

a. implement game simulstion in different ways

Here is the 4 types of functions to generate games

#' Dice game using a loop
#' @param n The number of plays
#' @return Total won/lost money

play_dice1 <- function(n){
  
  if(n <= 0) {return(0)}
  
  random_samples <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  
  SUM <- 0
  for(i in 1:n){
    SUM <- SUM -2
    if(random_samples[i] == 3 || random_samples[i] == 5) { SUM <- SUM + random_samples[i]*2}
  }
  
  return(SUM)
}

#' Dice game using using built-in R vectorized functions
#' @param n The number of plays
#' @return Total won/lost money

play_dice2 <- function(n){
  
  if(n <= 0) {return(0)}
  
  random_samples <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  
  D3 <- random_samples==3
  D5 <- random_samples==5
  
  SUM <- -n*2 + sum(D3)*6 +sum(D5)*10
  
  return(SUM)
}


#' Dice game using by rolling all the dice into one and collapsing the die rolls into a single table()
#' @param n The number of plays
#' @return Total won/lost money

play_dice3 <- function(n){
  
  if(n <= 0) {return(0)}
  
  random_samples <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  
  #in case any one is 0 times
  dice_factor <- factor(random_samples, levels = 1:6)

  dice_rolls <- table(dice_factor)
  
  SUM <- -n*2 + dice_rolls[3]*6 +dice_rolls[5]*10
  
  return(SUM)
}


#' Dice game using using one of the âapplyâ functions
#' @param n The number of plays
#' @return Total won/lost money

play_dice4 <- function(n){
  
  if(n <= 0) {return(0)}
  
  random_samples <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  
  D3 <- random_samples==3
  D5 <- random_samples==5
  
  D35 <- matrix(c(D3,D5),nrow = 2,byrow = TRUE)
  
  SUM <- -n * 2 + apply(D35,1,sum) %*% c(6,10)
  
  return(SUM)
}

We can further implement seed as a parameter in the function, here is a example using loop version. the result should be the same as above

#' Dice game using a loop
#' @param n The number of plays
#' @return Total won/lost money

play_dice1_setseed <- function(n,seed=1){
  
  set.seed(seed)
  
  if(n <= 0) {return(0)}
  
  random_samples <- sample(1:6, n, replace = TRUE)
  
  SUM <- 0
  for(i in 1:n){
    SUM <- SUM -2
    if(random_samples[i] == 3 || random_samples[i] == 5) { SUM <- SUM + random_samples[i]*2}
  }
  
  return(SUM)
}

play_dice1_setseed(3,1)
[1] -6
play_dice1_setseed(3000,1)
[1] 2162

e

In order to see whether it is a fair game, we need to see the expectation of the money for one game. Using the Monte Carlo idea, we can play the games multiple times and see the average of the money. If it is a fair game, it should be close to 0.

Moneysum <- 0

# sample the game using a loop
for (i in 1:100000) {
  Moneysum <- Moneysum + play_dice1(1)
}

Mean_money <- Moneysum/100000

print(paste("the average earning of the game is",Mean_money))
[1] "the average earning of the game is 0.68264"

\[ E(X)=1/6*(3*2+5*2)-2=0.6666667 \] From statistical calculation we know the expectation of the game is 0.666667. The Monte Carlo result is greater than 0 and is close to 0.666667. So from the Monte Carlo result this is not a fair game.
